liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Humanitarian organisation Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF), also known as Doctors Without Borders, says bullets were fired at its premises near the Al-Shifa Hospital where MSF staff and their families were sheltering. Over 100 people, including 65 children, who are sheltering at the location have run out of food, MSF said in a post on X. "We’ve been trying to evacuate them for the past three days," the organisation said. "MSF is asking the Israeli army and Hamas for a safe passage for them to leave the epicentre of intense fighting currently ongoing in Gaza City." The organisation said thousands of civilians, medical staff and patients are trapped in hospitals and other locations under fire in Gaza City.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Médecins Sans Frontières says its premises near Al-Shifa Hospital were shot at, food has run out

children.content: Humanitarian organisation Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF), also known as Doctors Without Borders, says bullets were fired at its premises near the Al-Shifa Hospital where MSF staff and their families were sheltering.
Over 100 people, including 65 children, who are sheltering at the location have run out of food, MSF said in a post on X.
"We’ve been trying to evacuate them for the past three days," the organisation said.
"MSF is asking the Israeli army and Hamas for a safe passage for them to leave the epicentre of intense fighting currently ongoing in Gaza City."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Patients and medical teams trapped inside the Al-Quds Hospital have been evacuated, the Palestine Red Crescent Society says. The humanitarian agency says it was a "challenging and perilous" evacuation, spurred by power outages and the lack of food and water. They later said the evacuated had been taken to Khan Younis. They also say the hospital had become a "threat to the lives of everyone inside due to the ongoing Israeli bombardment around the hospital and firing upon those inside". "It became impossible to continue providing the necessary medical care under these conditions," they said in a social media post on X. Israel said it had killed " approximately 21 terrorists" at Al-Quds on Wednesday, in return fire after fighters shot from the hospital entrance. Both Al-Quds Hospital and Israel have yet to comment on the evacuation.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A desperate shortage of fuel has led to the deaths of about 40 patients including three premature babies at the besieged Al-Shifa Hospital. The Hamas-run Gaza health ministry says people are unable to leave, as the encirclement of the hospital by Israeli troops makes it too dangerous, Middle East correspondent Allyson Horn reports. Watch the full report below: "Hamas says that Israeli tanks are at the gates of Al-Shifa and there has been heavy gun battles around the vicinity between Israeli troops and Hamas militants," she said. "Because they say they cannot leave, the Hamas-run ministry of health says that now doctors are having to dig mass graves in the vicinity of the hospital to bury those people that have died over the last few days." About 600 patients and 5,000 civilians are stuck sheltering inside the hospital, according to the ministry. Israel claims that Hamas uses the hospital as a shield for military operations, which Hamas and the hospital leadership have denied. The World Health Organization has said that Al-Shifa has stopped functioning as a hospital and that the situation there is perilous.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: NAB is pencilling in a quarter on quarter rise of 1.5%, which is above the Reserve Bank’s implied pick of about 1.3-1.4%. Senior economist Taylor Nugent at NAB said in a note that one-off increase to award salaries in some sector mean the quarterly growth rate will be high and shouldn’t be extrapolated. "The high award wage increase does in part reflect labour market conditions but provides a higher increase than what non-award wages are seeing and will be lower next year," he said. "A 15% level adjustment for more than 250,000 aged care workers does not reflect conditions in the macro backdrop. "We think Wage Price Index will be back around 0.9% quarter on quarter in Q4." The market consensus for the September quarter wage growth is at 1.3%, according to a Reuters poll.
